The code is not following the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). The `GenerateReport` and `PrintReport` methods are responsible for different tasks. According to SRP, a class should have only one reason to change. In this case, the `Report` class has two responsibilities - generating reports and printing them.

Here's how you can refactor it:
```csharp
public interface IReport {
    void Generate(); 
}

public class Report : IReport{
    public void Generate() {
        // generate report
    }
}

public class ReportPrinter {
    private readonly IReport _report;

    public ReportPrinter(IReport report) {
        _report = report;
    }

    public void PrintReport(){
         // print report using the instance of `_report`
    }
}
```
In this refactored code, we have created an interface `IReport` that declares a method `Generate()`. The class `Report` implements this interface and is responsible for generating reports. We also introduced another class `ReportPrinter` which has a dependency on the `IReport` interface (dependency inversion) to print reports, adhering to the Dependency Inversion Principle. This way we have separated concerns into different classes with single responsibility each.

